WEBVTT

1
00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:53.000
<v Mat Okafor>Thanks for joining the ad-hoc. Product agrees the pattern is worth tackling, but they want a crisp scope before assigning writers. Today we need to define what the reusable template actually contains and which regional needs must appear on day one.</v>

2
00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:29.000
<v Lucas Andersson>From EMEA, the template needs three sections at minimum: in-region data handling, rollout scope boundaries, and multilingual training assumptions. Those are the parts I keep rewriting for Corso and Istanbul.</v>

3
00:07:47.000 --> 00:08:05.000
<v Sophia Ramirez>AMER needs a compliance evidence section with control mappings, incident-notification language, and tenant-isolation examples. If we have those pre-approved, MetroPharma-style reviews get dramatically faster.</v>

4
00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:41.000
<v Mei Lin Tan>APAC needs the same core content, plus a localization lens. The template should make it easy to explain what is standard versus what requires local adaptation, especially for Japanese operating teams.</v>

5
00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:17.000
<v Mat Okafor>That sounds like one document with reusable modules rather than three separate documents. If product builds a base template and we add regional appendices, we can serve global consistency without losing local relevance.</v>

6
00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:53.000
<v Lucas Andersson>Exactly. Corso does not need the whole global story, but it does need confidence that our base answer is repeatable and governance-backed.</v>

7
00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:29.000
<v Sophia Ramirez>And MetroPharma would benefit from knowing the same response framework works in other regulated contexts, even if we never name the other customers.</v>

8
00:25:47.000 --> 00:26:05.000
<v Mat Okafor>Perfect. Facilitator, summarize the scope definition as a reusable compliance-and-localization template with core modules plus regional appendices. That summary is what I will take into next Wednesday&#x27;s director sync.</v>

